---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What hours count as after-hours in Hobart?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Anything called in between 6pm and 7am on a weekday, plus all day Saturday after 1pm, all day Sunday, and Tasmanian public holidays. The Anzac Day morning is treated as a public-holiday rate window even though some trades work the afternoon."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is the after-hours surcharge always charged, even if I cancel?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "If a van has left the depot the call-out fee applies, even if the issue resolves itself before we arrive. If you ring back within ten minutes of booking and we have not dispatched, there is no charge."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you charge more for jobs in West Hobart or up the mountain roads?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Travel inside the standard Hobart service zone — CBD, Sandy Bay, Battery Point, West Hobart, North Hobart, New Town, Glenorchy, Kingston, Bellerive and Lindisfarne — is included in the call-out. Fern Tree, Mount Nelson summit, Margate and beyond may attract a small distance loading after dark, which we quote up-front."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "If it can wait until 8am, what should I do overnight?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Shut the affected isolation valve, place a tray or towels to capture drips, leave the heater off if gas is involved, and ventilate the room. Take a photo with a timestamp. Ring us at 7am to be first on the morning roster — we hold two slots open every weekday for overnight call-backs."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Will I get a compliance certificate from an after-hours job?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes — any gas or water work that requires one is issued through the Consumer Building and Occupational Services portal the next business day, with a copy emailed to you. We do not skip paperwork because the job was at 2am."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="After-Hours Emergency Plumbing in Hobart — What We Charge & How We Triage | Hobart Gas Heater Service"
  description="Hobart after-hours plumbing call-outs explained: the surcharge between 6pm and 7am, the four fail-states that get a tradie out tonight, and what can wait until 8am tomorrow."
  canonical="https://hobartgasheaterservice.com.au/after-hours-emergency-plumbing-hobart/"
>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <main>
    <section class="hero">
      <h1>After-hours emergency plumbing in Hobart — what we charge and how we triage</h1>
      <p class="lede">It is twenty past nine on a Tuesday in July, the rain is sideways off the Derwent, and you have just heard a noise from under the laundry that should not exist. This page is the honest version of what happens when you ring us between 6pm and 7am — what the call-out costs, what we treat as a same-night job, and what we will gently push to first light tomorrow.</p>
      <p>Call <a href="tel:+61485939966">+61 485 939 966</a> any hour, or email <a href="mailto:quotes@hobartgasheaterservice.com.au">quotes@hobartgasheaterservice.com.au</a> if it can wait until breakfast.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>What the after-hours surcharge actually buys you</h2>
      <p>Our day rate runs from 7am until 6pm Monday to Friday. Outside those hours the call-out fee shifts to the after-hours rate, which covers travel from the depot in Glenorchy out to wherever the job is, the first thirty minutes on-site, and the van stock — usually enough for a temporary isolate-and-make-safe even if a full repair has to wait. Labour beyond the first half hour is charged in fifteen-minute blocks at the after-hours rate, which sits roughly forty per cent above the daytime figure. Public-holiday work is a tier higher again.</p>
      <p>It is worth knowing what you are paying for. A daytime job in Sandy Bay might have the van already in the area; an after-hours job means waking a tradie, getting them on the road from Lutana or Berriedale, and keeping a duty phone monitored by a second person so the next caller is not stranded. The surcharge funds that capacity, not a profiteering margin on your bad luck.</p>
      <h3>Four fail-states that get a same-night dispatch</h3>
      <p>Not everything that goes wrong at night is an emergency. We treat four scenarios as hard same-night jobs, no negotiation:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Active gas smell that does not clear with windows open.</strong> If you can still smell it after five minutes of cross-ventilation with the appliance off at the isolation valve, that is a Class A gasfitter dispatch, full stop. AS/NZS 5601.1 puts a clear duty on the responder to attend and test.</li>
        <li><strong>Burst pipe still flowing with the mains off, or no mains shutoff found.</strong> Most Hobart blocks have a TasWater meter near the front fence — if you cannot find it or it will not turn, we come out.</li>
        <li><strong>Hot water unit leaking and electrically live, or a gas storage unit venting.</strong> Either is a safety dispatch, not a "ring in the morning" job.</li>
        <li><strong>Sewerage backing into the house through a floor waste or shower drain.</strong> Health-hazard territory, particularly with kids or someone immunocompromised in the home.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>What we will (politely) push to 8am tomorrow</h2>
      <p>The other end of the triage is just as important. A dripping kitchen tap, a slow-clearing kitchen sink, a hot water unit that has tripped its overtemperature cutoff but is not leaking, a toilet that is running but able to be isolated at the wall — these are not 11pm jobs. We will talk you through a temporary make-safe over the phone (free) and book you the first available daytime slot, often before 9am the next morning. The cost difference between a Tuesday-night call-out and an 8am Wednesday visit is significant, and in our experience nine out of ten overnight calls fall into the latter category once we have asked five quiet diagnostic questions.</p>
      <p>The Tasmanian winter changes this picture a little. Between April and September we keep a second after-hours van on the road specifically because gas heater faults spike — pilot lights blow out in southerly fronts, thermocouples that have soldiered through fifteen winters finally give up, and a household with elderly residents in West Hobart or Lindisfarne genuinely cannot wait for daylight to get heat back. We weight those calls accordingly.</p>
      <h3>Standing maintenance vs reactive after-hours</h3>
      <p>The gas heaters in most Hobart homes are between fifteen and twenty years old. That is the design life of a typical Type A unit running roughly five months a year on a cold-maritime duty cycle. If your unit is in that age bracket and you have had two callouts in the past twelve months, the economics of a planned replacement quote start to beat reactive after-hours dispatch. We are happy to walk you through that math without selling you a unit you do not need.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
      <h3>What hours count as after-hours in Hobart?</h3>
      <p>Anything called in between 6pm and 7am on a weekday, plus all day Saturday after 1pm, all day Sunday, and Tasmanian public holidays. The Anzac Day morning is treated as a public-holiday rate window even though some trades work the afternoon.</p>
      <h3>Is the after-hours surcharge always charged, even if I cancel?</h3>
      <p>If a van has left the depot the call-out fee applies, even if the issue resolves itself before we arrive. If you ring back within ten minutes of booking and we have not dispatched, there is no charge.</p>
      <h3>Do you charge more for jobs in West Hobart or up the mountain roads?</h3>
      <p>Travel inside the standard Hobart service zone — CBD, Sandy Bay, Battery Point, West Hobart, North Hobart, New Town, Glenorchy, Kingston, Bellerive and Lindisfarne — is included in the call-out. Fern Tree, Mount Nelson summit, Margate and beyond may attract a small distance loading after dark, which we quote up-front.</p>
      <h3>If it can wait until 8am, what should I do overnight?</h3>
      <p>Shut the affected isolation valve, place a tray or towels to capture drips, leave the heater off if gas is involved, and ventilate the room. Take a photo with a timestamp. Ring us at 7am to be first on the morning roster — we hold two slots open every weekday for overnight call-backs.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="cta">
      <h2>Ring now if it cannot wait</h2>
      <p>If you have read this far and you are still not sure whether it is a tonight job or a tomorrow job, ring <a href="tel:+61485939966">+61 485 939 966</a> and ask. We do not charge for the conversation, and we would rather talk you through a safe make-safe than send a van that was not needed. Licensed under the Tasmanian Consumer Building and Occupational Services framework, working to AS/NZS 5601.1 for gas and AS/NZS 3500 for water, every job closed with the right paperwork.</p>
    </section>
  </main>
</Layout>
